title: Fix integer overflow for large step for Slice OP
body:
**Description**: Fix integer overflow for large step for Slice OP

**Motivation and Context**
- The crash in #9368, is caused by the model contains very large step for Slice op, the step is 1000000000 which is close to 2^30, the will cause SafeInt overflow at https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/74eaaad768e0a5ad5e65b818605383c73dece509/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/utils.h#L161, the variable `pitch` is `ptrdiff_t` which is platform specific, and the behavior after this integer overflow is undefined, in theory, if a large enough step is given, this will also repro on 64 bit system
- The fix is to clamp the step between [-dim, dim] for the corresponding dimension, since any steps over it will simply push over the boundary
- Switch to std::clamp for Slice and some minor code update

body:
**Describe the bug**
This is recent as of: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/9181. We were using an older version of onnxruntime with onnxruntime_PREFER_SYSTEM_LIB set without issue, but trying to update to the latest version fails because when a package is not found, aliasing does not work.

For example, 
```
if(onnxruntime_PREFER_SYSTEM_LIB)
  find_package(Flatbuffers)
  add_library(flatbuffers ALIAS flatbuffers::flatbuffers)
endif()
if(NOT TARGET flatbuffers::flatbuffers)
  add_subdirectory(external/flatbuffers EXCLUDE_FROM_ALL)
endif()
```

When Flatbuffers is not found, the call to `add_library` will fail because this target does not exist and therefore, cannot be aliased. Instead, the `add_library` call should be guarded by `if(TARGET)` or `if(Flatbuffers_FOUND)`. The same is true in a couple of other locations in the file all stemming from the same commit.

**Urgency**
None

**System information**

- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows or Ubuntu 20.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: commit da56f01
- Python version: 3.9

title: Only add aliasing to targets if the corresponding package was found
body:
This addresses: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/9403

One of the recent changes started using `onnxruntime_PREFER_SYSTEM_LIB` to determine if `find_package` should be called first before building the package from a submodule. However, the change does not handle the case when the package is not found correctly. For example:

```
if(onnxruntime_PREFER_SYSTEM_LIB)
  find_package(Flatbuffers)
  add_library(flatbuffers ALIAS flatbuffers::flatbuffers)
endif()
if(NOT TARGET flatbuffers::flatbuffers)
  add_subdirectory(external/flatbuffers EXCLUDE_FROM_ALL)
endif()
```

When `Flatbuffers` is not found, the call to `add_library` will fail because the target does not exist. Instead, the call to `add_library` should be guarded by a check for `Flatbuffers_FOUND`.

body:
**Describe the bug**
It seems as if Relu nodes that immediately follow Conv nodes are getting dropped during quantization (if included in ops_to_quantize). If I understand things correctly, then this should still give correct results if **unsigned** int8 is used for quantization because the quantization parameters for the output of the QLinearConv node are determined from the output of the Relu that follows the Conv node in the original model (negative values would then just get clipped to zero). But if **signed** int8 is used, then negative values don't get clipped anymore and the absence of the Relu leads to wrong results.
Using symmetrized activation also leads to wrong results, even if unsigned int8 is used (demonstrated in the attached script).

The solution for my specific use case could be to exclude Relu from the ops_to_quantize argument. Omitting the Relu from ops_to_quantize has the unwanted side effect that a Maxpool following the Relu doesn't get quantized anymore, however (separate issue: #9428).

**Urgency**

Development of a backend is blocked by this, so it would be great if someone could provide some insights as soon as possible.

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.9.1
- Python version: 3.8

**To Reproduce**
Run code below
 
```
import torch
import numpy as np
import onnx
import onnxruntime
from onnxruntime import quantization

IMAGE_SHAPE  = (1, 1, 1, 1)
KERNEL_SHAPE = (1, 1, 1, 1)

class ToyModel(torch.nn.Module):

        super().__init__()
        self.conv = torch.nn.Conv2d(out_channels = KERNEL_SHAPE[0],
                                    in_channels  = KERNEL_SHAPE[1],
                                    kernel_size  = KERNEL_SHAPE[2:],

        weight = torch.tensor(data  = 127*np.ones(KERNEL_SHAPE).astype("float32"),

                                              requires_grad = False)

class ToyDataProvider(onnxruntime.quantization.CalibrationDataReader):

        self.data = ({ input_name: prefac*np.ones(IMAGE_SHAPE).astype("float32") } for prefac in [-127,+127])

    def get_next(self):
        try: return next(self.data)

def CreateToyModels(unquantized_path, quantized_path):

    model = ToyModel()
    torch.onnx.export(model, (torch.empty(IMAGE_SHAPE, dtype=torch.float32)), unquantized_path)

    input_name = session.get_inputs()[0].name
```

```
Component for aggressive decoding. Find the bifurcation index of predicted tokens, between source tokens,
starting from previous suffix match index, and predicted tokens.
Concat predicted tokens, starting from bifurcation index, to the back
of current tokens. This forms the output tokens.
Detect suffix match index in source tokens, between source tokens and output tokens.
Detection is based on finding the appearances of last n-gram in output tokens
in source tokens.
A match is considered found if source tokens contain a single matching n-gram.
Return the index of the start of the n-gram in source tokens.
No matching if found if src tokens contain multiple or zero matching n-grams. Return -1.
```

**Describe the bug**

_What is the rationale for restricting CoreML inference to the CPU and would there be any reason to not change the methods'/ functions' signatures to include a parameter as to offer a _choice_ of Processing Unit Configuration?_

This may be a feature rather than a bug, but the rationale (possibly controlling inference precision?) for the current state is not obvious, hence before forking for my purposes and/ or proposing a PR, I figured it would be prudent to raise it as a question first.

Specifically, during the [loading of CoreML models](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/5b65f1cb44eee6d82b9ba3b91a43b5b4a74ccae8/onnxruntime/core/providers/coreml/model/model.mm#L175-L198), model configuration is currently [set](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/5b65f1cb44eee6d82b9ba3b91a43b5b4a74ccae8/onnxruntime/core/providers/coreml/model/model.mm#L189) to `MLComputeUnitsAll`, i.e. for the GPU and Apple Neural Engine (ANE) to be used.

However, at [prediction stage](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/5b65f1cb44eee6d82b9ba3b91a43b5b4a74ccae8/onnxruntime/core/providers/coreml/model/model.mm#L200-L288), prediction options are [set ](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/5b65f1cb44eee6d82b9ba3b91a43b5b4a74ccae8/onnxruntime/core/providers/coreml/model/model.mm#L215) to `MLComputeUnitsCPUOnly`.
This obviously renders the GPU and more importantly the ANE irrelevant. Which, for my use case, causes a _prohibitive_ performance impact, in other words: the models we're looking at _require_ acceleration.
Also, this setting is unfortunately _hard-coded_, i.e. can't be overridden by passing a parameter.

**Description**: Optimize python overhead of APEX amp

1. In AMP's post_backward_with_master_weights function, there is obvious purely Python overhead running on CPU, especially for this path.  https://github.com/NVIDIA/apex/blob/0c7d8e3fa9a095a1641a2290877436d0314b69c6/apex/amp/_process_optimizer.py#L176. In this phase, CUDA Stream is idle and totally wasted. 

    This PR optimized this overhead by moving the long Loop into C++ implementation. This helped reduce the idle time for CUDA streams, which waiting for CPU handling the long loops.
    
    - Using Huggingface 12 layer 768 hidden size, intermediate_size 3072, Bert-base-uncased models,  post_backward_with_master_weights took from the initially 10.647ms down to 0.910ms with this PR. 
    
        ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/138672138-0a0a85e6-f160-46cf-9236-c0d94f91c9a6.png)
  
        **End to End Before:**
        train_samples_per_second   = 2.549  its / second
        train_samples_per_second removing the first 200 steps as warming up: 
            > 201/1000 [01:23<05:06,  2.60it/s]
            > 999/1000 [06:30<00:00,  2.59it/s]
            > ( 999 - 201) / (390s - 83s) = 2.599 its  / second

        **End To End After:**
        train_samples_per_second   = 2.622  its / second
        train_samples_per_second removing the first 200 steps as warming up: 
            > 201/1000 [01:22<04:56,  2.69it/s]
            > 999/1000 [06:19<00:00,  2.67it/s]
            > ( 999 - 201) / (379s - 82s) = 2.687 its / second

        So the e2e throughput gains are:  2.86% (step 0 ~ 1000 averagely),  3.39% (excluding the first 200 steps as warming up)

    - On a Unilm (12 layer, hidden size 768) models, we see less reduction in the overall e2e iteration latecy. The reason is, we have less initial overhead (e.g. only 5.96ms) here, somehow because the model parameter sizes are smaller than Bert Large, so the memory allocation is much faster.  
     
        We run each experiments for 1000 steps, and get some benchmarks. The direct saving per iteration is shown as below, reducing post_backward_with_master_weights from 5.96ms to 1.78ms, 70% reduction. (under the hood, the changes reduced the purely CPU work time before launching CUDA kernels).
        
        **Targeted Overhead - Before:** 
        ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/138655143-c36f457d-a8a4-4b2d-8b40-11f655c5c7ea.png)

                > Iteration:  39%|███▊      | 999/2584 [05:12<07:44,  3.41it/s]
                > ( 999 - 201) / ( 312s - 78s) = 3.410256 iter/sec

        **End To End After:**
        iter_per_sec : 3.249210 iter/sec
        iter_per_sec removing the first 200 steps as warming up: 
                > Iteration:   8%|▊         | 201/2584 [01:18<11:17,  3.52it/s]
                > Iteration:  39%|███▊      | 999/2584 [05:07<07:36,  3.47it/s]

title: Avoid cudaStreamSync at the end of Forward/Backward

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
As ORTModule should match the behavior of nn.module, we don't need to explicitly introduce a cudaStreamSync at the end of each subgraph execution. 

**Addition cudaStreamSync at the end of forward**
As shown in the profiling result below, ORTModule run has an extra “cudaStreamSync” call at the end of forward section. This was introduced as the finalizing step for InferenceSession::PartialRun(). This behavior is copied from original InferenceSession::Run() code when we implemented PartialRun executor. 
However, PyTorch would automatically introduce “cudaStreamSync” if following CPU computation has dependency on a GPU tensor. In another word, ORT doesn’t need to introduce this call explicitly. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9906745/138220276-97592e36-01ff-42b9-bbf7-509db983895a.png)

**Warmup Patterns after cudaStreamSync** 
As we zoom in to the time segment following cudaStreamSync call, we can see a time window lasting ~4ms that GPU is barely utilized. As the tasks in compute stream are depleted with cudaStreamSync call, CPU needs to refill the compute stream from scratch. This resulted in the GPU starvation, as CPU is not able to launch the kernels fast enough, worsen by the fact that the scheduled kernels are short to complete (<10us). The starving situation is eventually relieved when a larger kernel kicks in, taking up >100 us, giving time for CPU to catch up with the scheduling work. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9906745/138220373-5db5f14e-22f7-44f5-a1db-3d98e86daecb.png)

body:
**Description**: 
Registers two new contrib ops for TensorRT plugins: [EfficientNMS](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT/tree/master/plugin/efficientNMSPlugin), [PyramidROIAlign](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT/tree/master/plugin/pyramidROIAlignPlugin) and [multilevelCropAndResizePlugin](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT/tree/master/plugin/multilevelCropAndResizePlugin), which are common operations in object detection networks.

**Motivation and Context**
- TensorRT plugins allow fused and efficient execution of common complex operations not natively supported by TensorRT.
- An ONNX graph that has been modified to use TensorRT plugins ops will normally not run in ORT because it fails graph validation.
- This PR implements contrib ops for these operations so that ORT accepts them, and the TRT-EP backend can execute them.
- Additional TensorRT plugins can be registered in the future by following this PR as an example.
